The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Tokio Marine in search of life partner

 GARIMA SINGH

 New Delhi, May 20: Japans largest insurer ? Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Company ? is planning to enter Indias burgeoning life insurance market through its fully-owned Singapore-based subsidiary Millea Asia.

 Millea Asia is the promoter of Iffco Tokio General Insurance Company, a private insurer which has been operating in India since 2001.

 We are looking out for some opportunity and are quite optimistic but we need to find the right partner, Takaaki Tamai, chief executive officer of Millea Asia Pte Limited, told The Telegraph.

 While Tamai maintained that there was no fixed time frame that the company was looking at, sources said Millea Asia has already started scouting for Indian partners.

 Following a similar route, Tokio Marine already entered the Chinese life insurance market one-and-half years back.

 Tokio Marines market share in China in the non-life segment is less than one per cent, despite the fact that it entered this segment a decade ago.

 Other markets where Tokio Marine has ventured in life insurance include the US, Japan, Malaysia, Brazil, Mexico and Thailand.

 Millea Asia, which has operations across 10 countries, has registered a gross premium of 77.5 billion yen in general insurance business for fiscal 2004-05. It is eyeing premium worth 35 billion yen for its life business in the current financial year.

 As for Iffco-Tokio General Insurance, the company plans to make its first capital infusion during the current financial year. 

 It will be in excess of Rs 50 crore at least. This will be our first infusion since inception. We will put in capital as an when needed for the expansion purposes, Tamai said.

 The current paid up capital of the company stands at Rs 100 crore.

 Iffco-Tokio reported premium worth Rs 501 crore for 2004-05 against Rs 323 crore clocked in 2003-04. It is eyeing premium income in the region of Rs 750 crore for the current financial year.

 The companys profit before tax stood at Rs 23.6 crore during the last financial year compared with Rs 14.5 crore in 2003-04.

 The company, which has settled claims worth Rs 209 crore in the last financial year, has been paying a 6 per cent dividend for the last three years.

 Iffco-Tokio General Insurance is a joint venture promoted by the Indian Farmers Fertiliser Cooperative (Iffco) and its associates who own 74 per cent of the equity and Tokio Marine and Nichido of Japan who have the balance 26 per cent.




